issue_comments.body:
you set pktdata = buf_temp + copy;
the next line is bytestream_get_buffer(&buf_temp, rt->flv_header + rt->flv_header_bytes, copy);
bytestream_get_buffer sets buf_temp = buf_temp + copy
so at this point buf_temp should be the same as pktdata, if they are not then iam really curious what i am missing

@vkalinsky said:

> FATE is happy (not sure that code covered though)

I don't think that code is covered as the swscale x86 asm is not bit-exact compared to the reference C implementation, and therefore not tested.

@michaelni 

> _ffmpeg allocates a few bytes more to allow simple SIMD in filters avoiding alot of special cases to handle odd ends_

How does it do that? As far as I grep, ffmpeg is using avpicture_get_size, which doesn't take into account those possible overreads.

commit_comments.body:
libavcodec/videotoolbox.c still has references to H264Context::pps:

> libavcodec/videotoolbox.c:107:35: error: no member named 'pps' in 'struct H264Context'
>     memcpy(p + 4, h->pps.data, h->pps.data_size);
> libavcodec/videotoolbox.c:109:17: error: no member named 'pps' in 'struct H264Context'
>     p += 4 + h->pps.data_size;

